2015-07-18 09:17:38,616 - get_review_data - ERROR - Found review with a helpful/funny string that does not conform to the expected format: 1 person found this review helpful 1 person found this review funny
Rest of the review's contents: ['Recommended', '987.6 hrs on record', 'Posted: March 18', 'Exceptionally good. The game provides a fairly unique mix of elements that produce for the player a huge experience through procedurally generated maps against a fairly wide range of enemies. The developer support for the game is active and ongoing; this isn\'t a game that receives updates only rarely; events are often, and new content is plentiful. For a new player, you can expect to be working your way through things for weeks, and even months before you will start to see the edges of the game. Bugs exist, but they are not as common as you might anticipate from forum posts; the game is reliable enough to play with satisfaction. Balance is also an issue in some small cases, but for the most part there is no \'right way\' to play, aside from a select few very-end-game situations, where inevitably certain strategies are more favourable. If you are determined and skilled enough, you can make anything work, and have fun. There is a second currency aside from that earned in-game, but it should be noted that Warframe has managed to entirely avoid the notion of pay-2-win. You -can- buy weapons and frames with real money, but in every case, you can also obtain those items through gameplay. There is a trading system that also allows players to trade that currency to one another; if you play enough, and are smart about it, you will never need to spend any money at all, a fact that I almost feel guilty about, having established more than enough fortune to see me through for years to come, I will likely never need to give another penny to the developers. Potentially this only means that someone else has, however. The action is as fast-paced as the player will demand, the demand of skill progresses comfortably as the player attempts higher-level missions, and there is also a tangible sense of progression the more you play, as you acquire new gear and upgrades. The only criticism I have is the \'archwing\', a recent addition that is in dire need of certain tweaks. It progresses comparatively slow, at a snail\'s pace, to the rest of the game, and it is only loosely integrated with the rest of the game. There are many opportunities where it would fit to have a mission progress into this gamemode, but for either practicality reasons, or the devs haven\'t thought of it, archwing exists as a fairly separate entity. Regardless, Warframe is a fantastic game, with plenty of interesting ways for a player to blast, snipe and slash their way through the universe. From me, this game receives a rare "highly recommended"; it is an example of what a free-to-play game should aspire towards. Edit: Oh yeah, you play as a magic space-ninja. Are you kidding me? What more do you want?']

I try, I honestly do. The parkour system in this game is so unnatural that I find myself avioding it because it feels chunky and uncontrollable-- it almost feels uncomplete. The style is very unique and I love it. Go thousands of years in the future, and place ancient samurai-like warriors on a backdrop of chaos, genocide, and a very mysterious history. Sure, it can get repetitive and is somewhat centered around grinding and farming, but if you're a fan of shooting, slashing, and appreciating art, this is the game for you. Plus the community is great. I don't know if I've wasted too many hours of my life in the ferocious battleground of PvP forums and region channels, or if Warframe's PvE atmosphere is just special, but it is extremely refreshing to consistently run across players that want to help and work together. The dev team, too, is excellent at pushing new content and listening in on feedback from the players. Oh, It's free. There's no reason not to grab some friends and give it a shot."]

2015-07-18 14:13:14,953 - get_review_data - ERROR - Found review with a helpful/funny string that does not conform to the expected format: 1 person found this review helpful 1 person found this review funny
Rest of the review's contents: ['Recommended', '987.6 hrs on record', 'Posted: March 18', 'Exceptionally good. The game provides a fairly unique mix of elements that produce for the player a huge experience through procedurally generated maps against a fairly wide range of enemies. The developer support for the game is active and ongoing; this isn\'t a game that receives updates only rarely; events are often, and new content is plentiful. For a new player, you can expect to be working your way through things for weeks, and even months before you will start to see the edges of the game. Bugs exist, but they are not as common as you might anticipate from forum posts; the game is reliable enough to play with satisfaction. Balance is also an issue in some small cases, but for the most part there is no \'right way\' to play, aside from a select few very-end-game situations, where inevitably certain strategies are more favourable. If you are determined and skilled enough, you can make anything work, and have fun. There is a second currency aside from that earned in-game, but it should be noted that Warframe has managed to entirely avoid the notion of pay-2-win. You -can- buy weapons and frames with real money, but in every case, you can also obtain those items through gameplay. There is a trading system that also allows players to trade that currency to one another; if you play enough, and are smart about it, you will never need to spend any money at all, a fact that I almost feel guilty about, having established more than enough fortune to see me through for years to come, I will likely never need to give another penny to the developers. Potentially this only means that someone else has, however. The action is as fast-paced as the player will demand, the demand of skill progresses comfortably as the player attempts higher-level missions, and there is also a tangible sense of progression the more you play, as you acquire new gear and upgrades. The only criticism I have is the \'archwing\', a recent addition that is in dire need of certain tweaks. It progresses comparatively slow, at a snail\'s pace, to the rest of the game, and it is only loosely integrated with the rest of the game. There are many opportunities where it would fit to have a mission progress into this gamemode, but for either practicality reasons, or the devs haven\'t thought of it, archwing exists as a fairly separate entity. Regardless, Warframe is a fantastic game, with plenty of interesting ways for a player to blast, snipe and slash their way through the universe. From me, this game receives a rare "highly recommended"; it is an example of what a free-to-play game should aspire towards. Edit: Oh yeah, you play as a magic space-ninja. Are you kidding me? What more do you want?']

2015-07-18 14:34:18,666 - get_review_data - ERROR - Found review with a helpful/funny string that does not conform to the expected format: 1 person found this review helpful 1 person found this review funny
Rest of the review's contents: ['Recommended', '49.3 hrs on record', 'Posted: November 20, 2014', "So, for those of you looking at this game, take heed. This is a free to play game, and while EVERYTHING (Except some vanity items) can be obtained without paying any real money, it still is a difficult game to get ground on as you have such limited space and the grind for anything in the game is long and hardly enjoyable after a few hours of the same mission over and over. If you are still interested, read onwards. You play as the equivalence of a space-ninja, with different suits with special abilities, guns that do awesome things, and of course, epic melee weapons. You have a pick of three suits at the start. Most suggest Excaliber, since he's the easiest to play (And trying to unlock him otherwise is so annoying), however I picked Loki at the start. This game really makes you think about what weapons and suits (Called Warframes) you use, but doesn't punish you for straying from the Tank/DPS/Support/Niche builds. As I said previously, I played Loki from the start, pouring 5$ into the game to get a melee weapon called the Obex (I wanted to punch guys in the face, okay?) which, both choosing Loki and Obex had me ridiculed, I didn't regret it. I teleported around the battlefield, used clones to keep myself alive, and again, punched guys in the face. I joined my friends clan and found the game was deeper than just punching guys, as there were giant wars between ingame factions, assassination attempts on yourself that made missions terrifying, and the epic grind for mighty gear. This lead me to have great times with my friends and their clan. Then...I ran into a few problems. A lot of missions use reformated versions of the same maps, enemies become generic, and the grind for gear is sluggish. It took me 17 tries to get all the blueprints for my second suit, Valkyr (Who's super attack makes her invincible and punch things) by fighting this one boss over and over....eventually after that the grind to get the materials for the blueprints themselves took longerl, then the grind for ingame money to pay to start the crafting.... Face it, with any MMO you are gonna grind a lot for good stuff, but here at least you're a space ninja, right? Wrong. You may be a badass space warrior, but stealth sections in the game are partially broken, as enemies will detect you irregardless if you are an invisible Loki, and stealth attacks aren't always insta-kill as they are advertised. Some enemies are so beefy stealth is the only options which is super hard unless you are playing a frame made specifically for stealth (Ashe and Loki), especially in missions where you fail if you are detected (I played during some Red-thingy event and got a free scarf). Even with all the typical problems most games in the genre has, this is a unique treasure and I would play it some more if I wasn't already into 5 games right now. I'd give this a 7.5/10. Oh, and by the way, they totally ripped their Infested from Halo. Just sayin'."]

Rest of the review's contents: ['Recommended', '338.4 hrs on record', 'Posted: May 15', "Long Review: Warframe is an incredible game and a joy to play. First of all, it is free and not pay-to-win. Everything in the game is unlockable to everyone, though you can purchase gear with real money. If you do spend real money, everything is reasonably priced, and can be quite even cheaper if you buy it with a 25%, 50% off, or 75% off discount, which are sometimes received as log-in rewards. However, not only is it free, its better than many pay-to-play games. The controls are fluid and logical. Enemy types are varied, and act very different from one another. (For example, one type of enemy grabs you and draws you over with a chain before attacking you with a sword, while another summons wild dog-creatures called drahk to kill you.) Weapons are fun to use, especially melee weapons (in my opinion) and more importantly, every weapon feels different. For example, swinging the giant axe known as the Scindo feels different from using the dual daggers known as the fang. Even similar assault rifles have unique quirks and feel different, like the boltor with its spikes capable of impaling foes onto walls when compared with the buzlok and its homing ability. On top of all that, there is just so much too do! I have play many many hours of this game, and I've still got so many things I still want to do. New warframes to make, new levels to get through, new weapons to make, new mastery ranks to pass, new bosses to fight, new components to get, new archwings to build, SO MUCH TOO DO!!! All these things come together and make a masterpiece. Warframe is an incredible game and I am confident is saying it is my favorite game of all time. Short Review: Pros: Great variety in enemies 100% Free Fun and unique abilities for warframes Hundreds of hours of content Some entertaining boss fights (Vor, Sargas, Salad V, and Stalker are all pretty great) Great customization in loadouts Melee combat is absurdly fun Not Pay-To-Win Cons: Minor Bugs (nothing too major or gamebreaking) Parkour is somewhat imprecise You will have to farm a lot for some materials (neural sensors, neurodes, and sometimes orokin cells) Overall Rating: 10/10"]

2015-07-18 20:41:29,820 - get_review_data - ERROR - Found review with a helpful/funny string that does not conform to the expected format: 1 person found this review helpful 1 person found this review funny
Rest of the review's contents: ['Recommended', '269.2 hrs on record', 'Posted: May 19', 'TL:DR below. But honestly, read the whole thing if you consider playing for the first time. Now me and Warframe have a bit of a "it\'s complicated" relationship. So let\'s do the nice things first and then I\'ll delve into the parts I don\'t like in particular or that just make me want to rush the Digital Extremes team with an axe. THE GOOD The gameplay and the general mechanics that the game presents as it\'s main strength (you playing as a space ninja with superpowers) are present, delivered and executed with grace. The game is fun to play and provides quite a lot of entertainment. Moreso if you have friends to play with, since the game is based around coop for up to four players (90% of the game is still solo-able, so you can still play even if you\'re a person who would totally hang out with other people, but *insert excuse*) Anyways the core game is solid, the forums active and the overall community feels good. The main premise of the gameplay can be summarized like this: Step 1: Disregard enemies Step 2: Acquire currency and resources from the corpses of said enemies. Step 3:Use the aforementioned to craft a weapon Step 4: Further personalize your playstyle by further modifying the weapons in your arsenal and your warframe Step 5: Return to Step 1 Well, disregarding enemies using various weapons, be it a bow capable of tearing through multiple foes with one arrow, a shotgun obliterating your enemies, a staff, a scythe, a massive hammer, kunai, inflato-ray, handheld chainsaws, sniper rifles, claws, high-powered gloves and shoes further enhancing your punches and kicks, a katana, a dog, a flying cube or anything they might\'ve added since I wrote this review is fun, and as you probably realized by now, you have a lot of options to choose from. So you can spend a lot of time either polishing your skills with one weapon or hoarding everything you come across and hugging your recent favorites while drooling in fetal position and chuckling softly later. The crafting system does its job and while some weapons are definitely hard to obtain, if you get to the point where you\'re able to get them, you probably don\'t mind sinking a few more hours into the game anyway. The game has a solid lore partially influenced by the decision of the players and a history shrouded in mystery so well, we can only keep guessing about who we actually play as. The story provides good support to the gameplay and keeps me intrigued. And mods. Oh boy. THE MODS Now, even though I laid before you the core gameplay I purposefully left out one feature, simply because the mods are both good AND bad. Every weapon and \'frame you come across is equipped with a number of empty mod slots. These can be filled with, you guessed it, modifications. Mods are numerous and their effects vary immensely, so the number of possible combinations to try is astronomical. BUT. Mods aren\'t acquired automatically or unlocked (several exceptions there, but that\'s like 1% of the total mod count). Mods have to be found from random drops. And given that a specific mod usually drops from a specific enemy, and that a) the chance for that is pretty low and b) the mob may be spawning in end-game levels only, it can and will frustrate some who try to just reach for that one mod they want so badly. Mods can be also improved in terms of effectivity, but that means destroying other mods to improve one, or using several \'Fusion Cores\' which give considerably larger bonuses and drop randomly from fallen enemies too. This system is slightly-above-average at best and downright rage-inducing at worst. Also the aforementioned customization is also limited by the player\'s own (hopefully) human conscience. In short there are mods that aren\'t worth squat and have no reason to exist whatsoever, since the bonuses they provide can\'t lift a candle against others. So, instead of making the most of what you\'ve got, you will spend hours/days chasing/fusing that one mod that will finally make your weapon usable in higher levels. There\'s even a mod that increases overall damage up to insane numbers, a must-have for endgame. So the mod system, while essential, is partially broken. There have been ideas on the forums on how to either rework or discard the system in favor of a new one, but I don\'t think that we will see any changes in the foreseeable future. THE STUFF THAT MAKES ME GO OHMYGODWHYISTHISSTILLATHINGAFTERAYEAR 1) The inventory For a game with so much custom-loadoutization, Warframe makes one very profitable (for them) and very infuriating (for you) choice. Adding an inventory system. Basically, you have (as of now) about 30 warframes and about 180 weapons. BUT. You can only have two warframes and six weapons in your inventory at once. There are two methods of expanding your inventory-either obtaining event weapons that come with their own separate slots, or purchase aditional slots with platinum (real cash). And while platinum can be obtained by trading with players and you get some at the beginning, most of it comes from real purchases for real cash by real players. 2) The grouping and hosting This one is pretty self-explanatory. Even though the number of mission crashes has significantly reduced with the removal of strict NATs, it\'s still an issue that can result in wasting a lot of your time and building up enough fury to start biting your table. Example: You spend 40+ minutes surviving in the void with a new reward coming each 5 minutes. All goes well, the drops are nice. Suddenly, everything around you freezes. You are now trapped inside you own private world, empty and lifeless, while your friends are overwhelmed and decide to finish the mission. When they leave, your mission crashes and all the rewards, experience, mods and so on are GONE. NO REFUNDS. And while you can submit a report, nobody will give you back those minutes you spent to earn absolutely nothing. THE GRAND FINALE Now while Warframe definitely has its issues, it is first and foremost a free game. And with 260.8+ hours under my belt I would be lying if I said that the game isn\'t entertaining enough to make me return to it ever so often. And that\'s why I recommend it, even though the rant above might turn away some of you. I recommend, because you can squeeze a great amount of fun out of this without spending a single penny. There\'s a reason why the game has such strong playerbase. It is definitely worth at least a try. And if you don\'t like it, you can always come back later to observe the changes. TL:DR It\'s fine. Give it a go. And maybe three more gos after the first one. Seriously, play this.']

2015-07-18 21:25:25,685 - get_review_data - ERROR - Found review with a helpful/funny string that does not conform to the expected format: 1 person found this review helpful 1 person found this review funny
Rest of the review's contents: ['Recommended', '510.5 hrs on record', 'Posted: November 3, 2014', '(Better review :D) Warframe, some may say it\'s the "Very definition of pay2win" well it\'s not, it\'s more of a grind2win game but at least you can play free without having to pay a single cent. Really the only moment you\'ll buy something is probably for a cosmetic or to rush your currently crafting items. In Warframe you play as a Tenno warrior, with the suit called a Warframe which has epic powers depending on which frame you have. There\'s a lot of variety between the frames, and many different primary, secondary and melee weapons to choose from. These primary, seconday and melee weapons you can find and craft from the market so long as you have the required recources. Warframes you can also buy from the market but you will need both recources and parts for the warframe, now onto other weapons and warframes. Clan weapons and warframes, they can only be found in a Clan Dojo and you must craft it in clan first then craft it at your foundry and a forma is needed for this. These weapons are significantly more powerful than the weapons found in the market. Community: helpful, nice Tenno friends, who will likely help you in a mission. You can also join players already in the middle of a mission and complete it along with them, the only con with this is that some players may kill faster than you. Mastery Rank: From what I\'ve noticed, ranking up your mastery rank will always have positive sides, access to stronger weapons on the market, othe rplayers lower level than you may feel better that you\'re there along side them to help. Ranking up is easy, all you need to do is rank up your new weapons/frames to rank 30 and repeat with new weapons. (But keep your high level weps for those high level missions) Potatoes: There are 3 different potatoes, Orokin Cells, Catalyst and Reactor, Cells allow you to build weapons and warframes that require cells, catalyst adds an extra 30 rank on your weapon of choice (make sure your wep is already level 30 for it to be bumped up to 60) and reactor adds another 30 to your warframe (again, amke sure your frame is already at rank 30.) Mods: No, not the mods you new players are thinking! Mods are for your weapons/warframe/sentinel/kubrow. Mods are used to make your weapons, warframe or companions stronger, you can find mods in any mission you do, just be sure you know what you\'re doing with what mods you have. and finally, companions!: Sentinels, little flying robots with guns, or robots that can help you pick up recources or mods. Kubrows, dog-like space things, although weaker than sentinels, they\'re cute as hell and make a good Liset pet! You can mod these lil guys and the sentinels, there are many different kind of kubrows, stealth kubrows, attack kubrows, recource kubrows etc. For better info visit the Warframe wiki!']

2015-07-18 23:06:02,224 - get_review_data - ERROR - Found review with a helpful/funny string that does not conform to the expected format: 1 person found this review helpful 1 person found this review funny
Rest of the review's contents: ['Recommended', '174.5 hrs on record', 'Posted: February 7', 'I haven\'t played a lot of warframe. I usually don\'t have the time to spend hours upon hours of time grinding and doing missions. But is it fun? Yes. Oh my god is it fun to play. You play as a Tenno, a conveniently amnesiac posthuman engineered bimechanical eldritch monstrosity (That was apparently trained as a Ninja samurai parkour Gunkata master assassin) in the grim darkness of the unspecified future, that is currently being opressed by an empire of genetically degraded space marines, a corporation of maniacs that literally worship profit, and a group of horrifying space-zombies. It is your job to go around and shoot/stab/cut/punch/explode/set on fire/other these groups. In order to do this, you have been granted a Liset, a fancy spaceship furnished with a damaged psychotic AI and only a few millenia of looting damage. With your ship, you are able to do missions on different planets, until you defeat the boss of the planet, which grants you the item necessary for the next planet, and so on and so forth. This brings us to the best part of warframe: Combat Your equipment consists of several things. First and foremost, your current warframe, representing you. Each different warframe has different abilities, as well as different base health, armor and shields. You also bring a primary weapon, a secondary weapon and a melee weapon. Combat consists of frantic, fast paced third person shooting, with the tenno constantly sprinting, jumping and backflipping around enemies, unleashing barrages of gunfire. No point of combat ever slows down: if you\'re not shooting people, you\'re either looting corpses or running around. The warframe powers are very varied, and fun too use, making practically every frame seem interesting. For example, Excalibur, the "all rounder" starting frame, has a rapid sprint melee attack, the ability to blind enemies, a "super jump" and "radial javelin", an attack that summons a bunch of golden javelins to stab people. Every frame has completely different abilities. At the end of each mission, you will receive loot, in the form of resources, credits, blueprints and mods. Resources are used to construct things in your forge based on the blueprints you have found, and credits are used to buy items that are available in the market (although most important items require in-game purchases). Mods are your main method for strengthening warframes. They can be attached to any (non-decorative) piece of equipment, and use to improve it. For example, giving your warframe shield enhancing mods, or equipping a specific stance mod for your melee weapon. Hell, do you want a bow that sets people on fire while freezing them? You can do that! I won\'t go into detail for the mod system, because that would take far too long. In fact, there are several things I won\'t talk about, like mastery ranks, clans, weapon types, kubrows, sentinels, archwings and mission types, simply because it would take far too long, and I believe you should experience these first hand. Warframe does, however, have one glaring irritation: There is SO MUCH GRINDING to do. Seriously, it takes forever to get any piece of equipment without buying it with real money. Speaking of in game purchases, these are also required for faster forging and inventory slots, so non-paying players may feel a tad restricted when managing their inventories. But the game isn\'t pay to win: any item that affects your abilities can be obtained without paying a cent, though it will take time. The art design is simply fantastic. The grineer are appropriately militaristic and boxy, their imperfections and augmentations defining them. The corpus are sleek, like actual space corporations would be like. The infested manage to actually FEEL wrong and disturbing without being generic space zombies. But the prize goes to the tenno designs: even the basic warframes look alien and otherwordly, with each frame being a completely different kind of awesome, but you have to account for different colors, helmets, skins, sigils, scarves, and so on. This has some crazy results IN SUMMATION pro + Frantic, satisfying fast paced combat + Supports several different playstyles + Everything looks awesome + Not pay to win con - Absurd grinding - Limited inventory Verdict 8/10 - GREAT!']

Rest of the review's contents: ['Recommended', '200.7 hrs on record', 'Posted: June 27', 'Pros:', 'Combat', 'Customization', 'Weapons', 'Warframes', 'Warframe powers', 'Beautiful scenery', 'F2P', 'Cons:', 'Grinding', 'High prices', 'Community', 'Trading system', 'Boring to play solo', 'Personal opinion:', "There is a TL;DR and the end of the review if you don't want to read the entire thing.", 'Warframe is F2P TPS action game. You are the Tenno, a member of the Tenno Order that served the Orokin race before it went extinct. The Orokin used the Tenno in The Old War to fight the Sentients, and although the Sentients won the Tenno survived. The Tenno went into stasis but now they have been reawaken again by the Lotus to fight the oppressive Grineer Empire. The Grineer are clones of the old human A.K.A. Orokin race that want to conquer and enslave the entire Solar System. It is your job to stop them. The combat in this game is pretty good. There are three modes to play in. The co-op mode (which is the standard mode) in which you team up with other players to complete missions all over the Solar System to collect rare resources, defend important objectives or assassinate enemy leaders. The second mode is the Conclave or the PvP mode in which you fight against other players (1 vs. All, 4 vs. 4. or capture the Cephalon). The last mode is the Archwing mode which is also a co-op mode in which you take control of an Archwing in order to complete missions in space. There is a huge selection of Warframes and weapons. Often times you\'ll find yourself not knowing which weapon or warframe you want to build next, but there are tons of wikipedia articles and YouTube videos that explain each warframe and weapon specifically, so if you do some research you shouldn\'t have a problem with choosing your frames and weapons. There are also special kind of warframes and weapons which have more modding options and are stronger, and they are called Prime items. They are obtainable from the Orokin Void, but be prepared to grind for them as getting them is really hard. Warframe powers are the best part of the game. Each warframe has 4 powers at it\'s disposal and they can be made stronger with special mods. As you rank up you waframes you will unlock new powers and existing ones will get stronger. Some waframes have support powers which help your teammates, other warframes have healing powers while other have strong damage powers. This truly is a great F2P game in that it\'s not P2W in any way AND you can get anything, anything in this game, permanently, for free if you work hard enough! Want to buy that awesome armor set or syandana? Just trade a bunch of prime parts for platinum and you\'re good to go. But of course, if you don\'t want to grind for items or wait for too long you can always buy some platinum, but I would wait for a discount (you can get one as a log-in reward.) Now for the bad stuff... This game requires a lot and a lot of grinding if you want to have all the cool toys that other people have. For instance, I\'ve played this game for a 150 hours already, and only now have I made my first prime Warframe. There are also long wait times in this game (you have to wait for 3 days for your warframe to be crafted). But... Since this is a F2P game and you can get anything for free as I\'ve said earlier, I think we can forgive the developers for this, right? The community is, unfortunantely, a real downer in this game. It\'s not the same in some games like DayZ or Star Wars: The Old Republic where people actually want to know each other (I\'m not saying those game have great communities either, but still). It\'s really hard to find someone to show you the ropes or a friendly community clan IMO, that\'s why I suggest you get some friends to download the game so that you can play the game together. Heck, I can\'t play Warframes unless I\'m on Skype with my friends and we\'re doing missions together. But that does not mean you can\'t play Warframe solo either. There are warframes that are suited to players who like to play solo, like the Ash warframe for instance. The trading system (while it does work and I use it frequently), is really poorly done in my opinion. There is a single channel for the entire server and it\'s really hard to find someone to sell your gear to, there are also people who will try to scam you, so beware of them. And the trading is also limited, but we might see an improvement in the future. For now it\'s "good enough" but it could be better. TL;DR: A great F2P game with great combat and customization. You can get anything, literally anything for free if you\'re not lazy to grind for items etc. There is space for improvement in the trade system and the community could be a little more friendly, but it\'s still a great game to play with your friends.', 'Score:', '9/10']
